docs.lead_paragraph: The Pennsylvania Inquirer says: Dr. Henry S. Patterson, the distinguished Professor of Matera Medica and Therapeutics in the Medical Department of Pennsylvania College, has withdrawn from the active duties of that Chair, in consequence of enfeebled health, and has been transferred to the Emeritus Professonship.

headline.main: LATEST INTELLIGENCE.; By Telegraph to the New-York Daily Times. IMPORTANT FROM THE CAPITAL. England and France on the Austrian Prenuncuamento, and other Interesting Intelligence. The Yellow Fever at the South. " Ten Hours" State Convention in Massachusetts. Nominations in Eric County--Illeness of Judge Mullett--Senator Shields. Gule on Late Michigan--Loss of two Vessels. Heavy Storm at the East-Destruction of the Telegraph Lines. Progress of the Trials for Forgery. The Cholern In Maryland-Cumberland Ceal Trade. Delegate to the Whig State Convention. Hunker Movement in Ononlaga County. False Rumor. Political Nominations at Buffalo. Courty of Appeas. The Sloop-of-war Cyane.

docs.lead_paragraph: The Union, to-morrow, will publish HULSEMANN'S letter relative to the KOSZTA case, and MARCY'S reply. So far from England and France having united in the remonstrance against INGRAHAM'S conduct at Smyrna, France has actually indicated to Austria its disapprobation of the proceedings of her officers, admitting the circumstances to be correctly set forth in the Vienna Pronunciamento.

docs.lead_paragraph: We have received later intelligence from Texas, including Galveston dates to the 16th instant, and Indianola papers to the 13th. We see it stated in the Galveston Journal, of the 15th, that the steamship Louisiana, which was to have sailed on the previous Sunday evening for this port, was detained until the following evening from sickness among the passengers and crew, resulting in the death of one before she left.

docs.lead_paragraph: THE FAVER IN GALVESTON.--The Journal of the 15th says the city sexton has made the following report of the interments. Sept. 12, 18; Sept 13, 9; Sept. 14, 12--total. 39. The most of these cases wer taken previous to the present clear and pleasant weather. The South breeze which has prevailed for the last two or three days is considered quite favorable to the health of well persons.
